   {:e #blake3 "5063e365a0ba997c2f8db7fa5aac8f915361a60f067034fb938797a598f416b8" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "DELIBERATION: What is the single highest-leverage addition? Candidates under consideration:\n\nCANDIDATE A: Auto-transact COF hints (ZCM-1). Already planned. High leverage but OBVIOUS — it's the direct fix for the ceremony-flow tension. Not non-obvious.\n\nCANDIDATE B: Make spec-language indistinguishable from code-language. Transcript 05 insight: 'don't strengthen Basin A — make Basin B unavailable.' But this is architectural aspiration, not a concrete addition.\n\nCANDIDATE C: Learned context precedence — track which ACP context blocks agents actually USE and auto-promote/demote based on observed behavior. This is significance accumulation applied to output. Non-obvious, compounding (gets better with use), defensible (data-driven, not heuristic).\n\nCANDIDATE D: Store-mediated code access — all file reads go through the store, creating datoms as side effects. This makes Basin B structurally unavailable but is a massive engineering investment.\n\nCANDIDATE E: Turn the projection algebra into a BIDIRECTIONAL channel — not just store→agent output, but agent→store INPUT parsing. Every agent message that references a spec ID, task ID, or braid command auto-transacts a provenance datom. This makes the agent's OWN OUTPUTS feed the store, closing the observation gap without any ceremony.\n\nEvaluating: E is the most non-obvious. It's the INVERSE of auto-observation — instead of the SYSTEM observing what the AGENT does, the SYSTEM parses what the AGENT SAYS. The agent's natural language output already contains spec references, task IDs, decisions, and reasoning. These are IMPLICIT observations. Extracting them into datoms is zero-cost to the agent and creates a continuously-densifying knowledge graph.\n\nBut wait — E requires parsing agent messages, which braid doesn't have access to (it only sees its own CLI output, not the agent's text). Unless... the MCP tool call arguments contain the agent's reasoning. The 'arguments' field of every MCP tool call IS the agent's intent expressed as structured data. This is already available.\n\nActually, the DEEPEST candidate is something else entirely...\nSession entity: :task/t-02bc60a0; Session entity: :task/t-c3d9f38c; Session entity: :task/t-641dd8a6; Session entity: :task/t-59196416; Session entity: :task/t-2b2fd6eb; Session entity: :task/t-a8fc2cee; Session entity: :task/t-78bc87d7; Session entity: :task/t-caa01560" :op :assert}
